  "text": "When statistical comparisons with a \"healthy\" group is not feasible, assumptions must be made about which physiological frequencies are clinically relevant. Some assumptions are based on physiological feasibility: for example, frequencies above 20 Hz are likely too rapid to affect balance-related processes or neurophysiological dynamics at the whole-body level. Other assumptions are premised on the distribution of spectral power. For instance, the preponderance of spectral power (95%) of quiet standing COP exists at frequencies lower than 1 Hz [CITATION_1] . However, the majority of the studies in our systematic review examined frequencies greater than 1 Hz and some identified statistically significant results.",
